Here's a complete example for your C# MCP server:

---

**Program.cs** — stdio transport with DI:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC protocol channel
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

// Register HttpClient via DI (IHttpClientFactory + typed HttpClient)
builder.Services.AddHttpClient("api", client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

**PostApiTools.cs** — tool class wrapping a REST API:

```csharp
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Net.Http.Json;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

[McpServerToolType]
public class PostApiTools(IHttpClientFactory httpFactory, ILogger<PostApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a post by its numeric ID from the API.")]
    public async Task<string> GetPost(
        [Description("The post ID (1-100)")] int id,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching post {Id}", id);
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("api");
        var post = await client.GetFromJsonAsync<Post>($"/posts/{id}", cancellationToken);
        return $"Title: {post!.Title}\n\n{post.Body}";
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Search posts by user ID.")]
    public async Task<string> GetPostsByUser(
        [Description("The user ID to filter by")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("api");
        var posts = await client.GetFromJsonAsync<Post[]>(
            $"/posts?userId={userId}", cancellationToken);
        return string.Join("\n---\n", posts!.Select(p => $"[{p.Id}] {p.Title}"));
    }

    private record Post(int Id, int UserId, string Title, string Body);
}
```

---

## How DI Works for MCP Tools

The SDK uses **two injection styles**:

| Style | How it works |
|-------|-------------|
| **Constructor injection** (non-static class) | Services like `IHttpClientFactory`, `ILogger<T>` are injected via primary constructor. The class is resolved from the DI container per-request. |
| **Method parameter injection** (static class) | DI services can appear directly as method parameters — the SDK resolves them automatically. |

**Key rule:** The SDK distinguishes tool *inputs* (parameters with `[Description]`) from *injected services* (known types like `CancellationToken`, `ILogger`, or any DI-registered service). Only described parameters appear in the JSON schema sent to LLMs.

To scaffold this project from scratch:

```bash
dotnet new mcpserver -n MyApiServer
cd MyApiServer
dotnet add package Microsoft.Extensions.Http
dotnet build
```

Then replace the generated files with the code above. Run with `dotnet run` — it will listen on stdin for JSON-RPC messages from an MCP client.
